Since you cannot install Python and have no time to set up an environment, the only way to do this is using **Google Sheets**. 

It is the "industry standard" for quick ops tools. It requires **zero installation**, it's a "working script" (Apps Script), and it looks professional during a demo because it's a visual dashboard, not a black command-screen.

**Follow these 5 steps exactly. It will take you 10 minutes.**

### Step 1: The Sheet
1. Open a new **Google Sheet**.
2. Rename the first tab to `Inventory`.
3. In cell **A1**, type `Item Name`. In **B1**, type `Current Stock`. In **C1**, type `Price`.
4. Fill in 3 rows of fake data (e.g., "Laptops", "10", "1200").

### Step 2: The Script
1. In the top menu, go to **Extensions** $\rightarrow$ **Apps Script**.
2. A new window will open. Delete any code already there.
3. **Copy and paste this exact code:**

```javascript
function onOpen() {
  var ui = SpreadsheetApp.getUi();
  ui.createMenu('📦 Inventory Management')
      .addItem('Update Stock Level', 'updateStock')
      .addItem('Low Stock Alert', 'checkLowStock')
      .addToUi();
}

function updateStock() {
  var ui = SpreadsheetApp.getUi();

  var itemResponse = ui.prompt('Update Stock', 'Enter the exact Item Name:', ui.ButtonSet.OK_CANCEL);
  if (itemResponse.getSelectedButton() != ui.Button.OK) return;
  var itemName = itemResponse.getResponseText();

  var qtyResponse = ui.prompt('Update Stock', 'Enter quantity to ADD (use negative number to subtract):', ui.ButtonSet.OK_CANCEL);
  if (qtyResponse.getSelectedButton() != ui.Button.OK) return;
  var qty = parseInt(qtyResponse.getResponseText());

  var sheet = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet().getSheetByName('Inventory');
  var data = sheet.getDataRange().getValues();

  for (var i = 1; i < data.length; i++) {
    if (data[i][0] == itemName) {
      var newQty = data[i][1] + qty;
      sheet.getRange(i + 1, 2).setValue(newQty);
      ui.alert('Success: ' + itemName + ' is now at ' + newQty);
      return;
    }
  }
  ui.alert('Error: Item not found.');
}

function checkLowStock() {
  var sheet = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet().getSheetByName('Inventory');
  var data = sheet.getDataRange().getValues();
  var lowItems = [];

  for (var i = 1; i < data.length; i++) {
    if (data[i][1] < 5) { // Alerts if stock is less than 5
      lowItems.push(data[i][0] + " (Only " + data[i][1] + " left)");
    }
  }

  var ui = SpreadsheetApp.getUi();
  if (lowItems.length > 0) {
    ui.alert('⚠️ LOW STOCK ALERT:\n\n' + lowItems.join('\n'));
  } else {
    ui.alert('All stock levels are healthy.');
  }
}
```

### Step 3: Save and Refresh
1. Click the **Disk icon (Save)** at the top and name it "Inventory System".
2. **Go back to your Google Sheet tab and refresh the page in your browser.**

### Step 4: The "Activation" (Crucial)
1. Look at your Google Sheet menu. You will now see a new menu item called **`📦 Inventory Management`**.
2. Click it $\rightarrow$ Click **Update Stock Level**.
3. Google will say "Authorization Required." 
4. Click **Continue** $\rightarrow$ **Choose your account** $\rightarrow$ **Advanced** $\rightarrow$ **Go to Inventory System (unsafe)** $\rightarrow$ **Allow**. 
   *(Don't worry, it's "unsafe" only because you wrote it yourself and didn't pay Google to verify it).*

### Step 5: The Demo
Now you have a professional tool. To impress the team:
1. Show the sheet.
2. Click **Inventory Management** $\rightarrow$ **Update Stock Level**.
3. Enter "Laptops" and "5". Watch the number in the sheet change automatically.
4. Change a number in the sheet to "2" manually, then click **Inventory Management** $\rightarrow$ **Low Stock Alert**. It will pop up a warning.

**What to tell your team:**
*"I've implemented a cloud-based automation script integrated directly into our sheets to eliminate manual data entry errors and provide real-time low-stock alerts. We can scale this to a full database later, but this gets us operational immediately."*

I understand. The panic is real, but we are going to solve this right now.

Since you cannot install software, create accounts, or risk a technical glitch, you cannot "build" anything. **However, you can use a "Simulator."**

I have written a single piece of code below. You do not need to install anything. You do not need an account. You just need a web browser (Chrome, Edge, or Safari).

### Exactly what to do (3 minutes):
1. Open a simple text editor on your computer (like **Notepad** on Windows or **TextEdit** on Mac).
2. **Copy and paste the entire block of code below into that blank file.**
3. Save the file to your desktop as **`System.html`** (Make sure it ends in `.html`, not `.txt`).
4. **Double-click that file.** It will open in your web browser.

**That is it. You now have a professional-looking, interactive dashboard that works offline and requires no setup.**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Ops Inventory Management System</title>
    <style>
        body { font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif; background: #f4f7f6; margin: 0; padding: 20px; }
        .header { background: #2c3e50; color: white; padding: 20px; text-align: center; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 20px; }
        .container { max-width: 900px; margin: auto; background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; box-shadow: 0 4px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1); }
        table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 20px; }
        th { background: #ecf0f1; text-align: left; padding: 12px; border-bottom: 2px solid #ddd; }
        td { padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd; }
        .btn { padding: 6px 12px; cursor: pointer; border: none; border-radius: 4px; font-weight: bold; margin: 0 5px; }
        .btn-plus { background: #27ae60; color: white; }
        .btn-minus { background: #c0392b; color: white; }
        .status-low { color: red; font-weight: bold; }
        .status-ok { color: green; font-weight: bold; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="header">
    <h1>📦 Senior Ops: Inventory Tracking System v1.0</h1>
    <p>Real-time Asset Management Dashboard</p>
</div>

<div class="container">
    <h3>Current Stock Levels</h3>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Item Name</th>
                <th>Quantity</th>
                <th>Status</th>
                <th>Actions</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody id="inventory-body">
            <!-- Data rows will appear here -->
        </tbody>
    </table>
</div>

<script>
    // This is the "Database" - you can change these names and numbers right here if you want
    let inventory = [
        { name: "Industrial Sensors", qty: 45 },
        { name: "Control Valves", qty: 12 },
        { name: "Replacement Gaskets", qty: 4 },
        { name: "Hydraulic Pumps", qty: 28 }
    ];

    function renderTable() {
        const body = document.getElementById('inventory-body');
        body.innerHTML = '';

        inventory.forEach((item, index) => {
            const status = item.qty < 10 ? '<span class="status-low">LOW STOCK</span>' : '<span class="status-ok">HEALTHY</span>';
            body.innerHTML += `
                <tr>
                    <td>${item.name}</td>
                    <td><strong>${item.qty}</strong></td>
                    <td>${status}</td>
                    <td>
                        <button class="btn btn-plus" onclick="changeQty(${index}, 1)">+</button>
                        <button class="btn btn-minus" onclick="changeQty(${index}, -1)">-</button>
                    </td>
                </tr>
            `;
        });
    }

    function changeQty(index, amount) {
        inventory[index].qty += amount;
        if(inventory[index].qty < 0) inventory[index].qty = 0;
        renderTable();
    }

    renderTable();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How to handle the meeting (The "Safe" Plan):
1. **Open the file** on your screen *before* the team walks in.
2. **Keep it full screen.**
3. **The Demo:** Click the `+` and `-` buttons. The numbers change instantly, and the "Status" flips from "HEALTHY" to "LOW STOCK" if the number drops below 10.
4. **What to say:**
   *"I've developed a front-end prototype focused on user experience. I wanted to ensure the workflow for the operators was seamless before we hook it up to the main server. As you can see, the logic for the low-stock triggers is already functional. This is the blueprint we'll be using for the full rollout."*

**You are now safe.** No accounts, no installs, no authorization. Just a file on your desktop. You can do this.
